I"©<p>When one is trying not to seek <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/logic-frameworks-formalize-truth">truth</a> in an argument, but rather to defend their <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/self-alignment-guides-meaning-making">sense of self</a>, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/perception-is-context-dependent">reality gets distorted</a> in such a way as to <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/affect-reflects-ideological-structures">enable a coherent identity</a>. In this, motivated reasoning degrades quality of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/diversity-in-problem-solving-sidesteps-ideological-debt">problem solving</a>.</p>
